hat property gets ignored at runtime. I think application classes are typically runtime-initialized by default, with only some requiring build-time initialization.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing resource leak detection setup**\\n\\nI'm diving into the ResourceLeakDetector setup. It starts with initializing the factory and checking the test class with Class.forName. Good to know the static block initializes properties correctly; it seems okay for JUnit instantiation. However, I’m slightly concerned about class loading and whether static imports affect this. I’ll need to adjust the build.gradle to ensure properties are set for the JVM. Importantly, should I restore system properties after running tests? Considering AtomicInteger for thread safety seems wise. I should make necessary imports.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering ResourceLeakDetector functionality**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the ResourceLeakDetectorFactory. If the custom class constructor is null, it likely means metadata is missing, causing Class.forName to fail. In that case, the default detector would be returned, and the assertion would fail. However, once the metadata is generated properly, I expect it to succeed afterward. It's crucial that this flow is handled correctly to avoid false failures in detection. I want to ensure that everything is correctly managed for reliable performance.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering JUnit extensions**\\n\\nI'm trying to figure out how JUnit can instantiate a class with a parameterized constructor using a nested extension. The challenge is that the extension is part of the test class being constructed, which raises the question: is the extension loaded before the constructor? It seems that JUnit reads class metadata before creating an instance, allowing it to instantiate a static nested extension using a no-argument constructor. I’m curious about how this all connects!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_JTHl17ScslnwzQM6SxQF9F2D|fc_03ea9111bf0888220169fdede1c5ac819ca7dd3ddd9187c19d", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.netty/netty-all/4.0.38.Final/src/test/java/io_netty/netty_all/ResourceLeakDetectorFactoryInnerDefaultResourceLeakDetectorFactoryTest.java", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage io_netty.netty_all;\n\nimport io.netty.util.ResourceLeakDetector;\nimport io.netty.util.ResourceLeakDetectorFactory;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.extension.ExtendWith;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.extension.ExtensionContext;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.extension.ParameterContext;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.extension.ParameterResolver;\n\nimport java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicInteger;\n\nimport static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;\n\n@ExtendWith(ResourceLeakDetectorFactoryInnerDefaultResourceLeakDetectorFactoryTest.ConstructorParameters.class)\npublic class ResourceLeakDetectorFactoryInnerDefaultResourceLeakDetectorFactoryTest extends ResourceLeakDetector<Object> {\n    private static final String CUSTOM_LEAK_DETECTOR_PROPERTY = \"io.netty.customResourceLeakDetector\";\n    private static final AtomicInteger CONSTRUCTOR_INVOCATIONS = new AtomicInteger();\n\n    private static volatile Class<?> lastResource;\n    private static volatile int lastSamplingInterval;\n    private static volatile long lastMaxActive;\n\n    static {\n        System.setProperty(\n                CUSTOM_LEAK_DETECTOR_PROPERTY,\n                ResourceLeakDetectorFactoryInnerDefaultResourceLeakDetectorFactoryTest.class.getName());\n    }\n\n    public ResourceLeakDetectorFactoryInnerDefaultResourceLeakDetectorFactoryTest(\n            Class<?> resource, int samplingInterval, long maxActive) {\n        super(resource, samplingInterval, maxActive);\n        lastResource = resource;\n        lastSamplingInterval = samplingInterval;\n        lastMaxActive = maxActive;\n        CONSTRUCTOR_INVOCATIONS.incrementAndGet();\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    void createsCustomResourceLeakDetectorFromSystemProperty() {\n        System.setProperty(CUSTOM_LEAK_DETECTOR_PROPERTY, getClass().getName());\n        int invocationsBeforeFactoryCall = CONSTRUCTOR_INVOCATIONS.get();\n\n        ResourceLeakDetector<StringBuilder> detector = ResourceLeakDetectorFactory.instance()\n                .newResourceLeakDetector(StringBuilder.class, 1, 7L);\n\n        assertThat(detector).isInstanceOf(ResourceLeakDetectorFactoryInnerDefaultResourceLeakDetectorFactoryTest.class);\n        assertThat(CONSTRUCTOR_INVOCATIONS.get()).isGreaterThan(invocationsBeforeFactoryCall);\n        assertThat(lastResource).isSameAs(StringBuilder.class);\n        assertThat(lastSamplingInterval).isEqualTo(1);\n        assertThat(lastMaxActive).isEqualTo(7L);\n    }\n\n    public static final class ConstructorParameters implements ParameterResolver {\n        @Override\n        public boolean supportsParameter(ParameterContext parameterContext, ExtensionContext extensionContext) {\n            Class<?> parameterType = parameterContext.getParameter().getType();\n            return parameterType == Class.class || parameterType == int.class || parameterType == long.class;\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public Object resolveParameter(ParameterContext parameterContext, ExtensionContext extensionContext) {\n            Class<?> parameterType = parameterContext.getParameter().getType();\n            if (parameterType == Class.class) {\n                return Object.class;\n            }\n            if (parameterType == int.class) {\n                return 1;\n            }\n            return Long.MAX_VALUE;\n        }\n    }\n}\n"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1403, "output": 3176, "cacheRea